[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] In computational complexity theory, **DSPACE** or **SPACE** is the computational resource describing the resource of memory space for a deterministic Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] It represents the total amount of memory space that a "normal" physical computer would need to solve a given computational problem with a given algorithm.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] The measure **DSPACE** is used to define complexity classes, sets of all of the decision problems that can be solved using a certain amount of memory space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] For each function *f*(*n*), there is a complexity class SPACE(*f*(*n*)), the set of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine using space *O*(*f*(*n*)).
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] There is no restriction on the amount of computation time that can be used, though there may be restrictions on some other complexity measures (like alternation).
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Several important complexity classes are defined in terms of **DSPACE**.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Let *x* be an input of smallest size, denoted by n, that requires more space than *k*, and ${\mathcal {C}}$ be the set of all configurations of *M* on input *x*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Let *S* denote the set of all possible crossing sequences of *M* on *x*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Note that the length of a crossing sequence of *M* on *x* is at most $|{\mathcal {C}}|$ : if it is longer than that, then some configuration will repeat, and *M* will go into an infinite loop.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] According to pigeonhole principle, there exist indexes *i* < *j* such that ${\mathcal {C}}_{i}(x)={\mathcal {C}}_{j}(x)$ , where ${\mathcal {C}}_{i}(x)$ and ${\mathcal {C}}_{j}(x)$ are the crossing sequences at boundary *i* and *j*, respectively.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Let x' be the string obtained from x by removing all cells from *i* + 1 to *j*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] The machine M still behaves exactly the same way on input x' as on input x, so it needs the same space to compute x' as to compute x.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] However, |*x'*| < |*x*|, contradicting the definition of x.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] The above theorem implies the necessity of the space-constructible function assumption in the space hierarchy theorem.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] Since many symbols might be packed into one by taking a suitable power of the alphabet, for all *c* ≥ 1 and *f* such that *f*(*n*) ≥ *1*, the class of languages recognizable in *cf*(*n*) space is the same as the class of languages recognizable in *f*(*n*) space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] This justifies usage of big O notation in the definition.
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] The space hierarchy theorem shows that, for every space-constructible function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , there exists some language *L* that is decidable in space $O(f(n))$ but not in space $o(f(n))$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/dspace] by a result of Williams, improving an older bound of $O(t/\log t)$ by Hopcroft, Paul, and Valiant.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In computational complexity theory, the **Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem** states that nondeterministic space complexity classes are closed under complementation.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It was proven independently by Neil Immerman and Róbert Szelepcsényi in 1987, for which they shared the 1995 Gödel Prize.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In its general form the theorem states that NSPACE(*s*(*n*)) = co-NSPACE(*s*(*n*)) for any function *s*(*n*) ≥ log *n*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The result is equivalently stated as NL = co-NL; although this is the special case when *s*(*n*) = log *n*, it implies the general theorem by a standard padding argument.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The result solved the second LBA problem.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] In other words, if a nondeterministic machine can solve a problem, another machine with the same resource bounds can solve its complement problem (with the *yes* and *no* answers reversed) in the same asymptotic amount of space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] No similar result is known for the time complexity classes, and indeed it is conjectured that NP is not equal to co-NP.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The principle used to prove the theorem has become known as inductive counting.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It has also been used to prove other theorems in computational complexity, including the closure of LOGCFL under complementation and the existence of error-free randomized logspace algorithms for USTCON.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The theorem is obtained from this special case by a padding argument.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The st-connectivity problem asks, given a digraph *G* and two vertices *s* and *t*, whether there is a directed path from *s* to *t* in *G*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This problem is NL-complete, therefore its complement *st-non-connectivity* is co-NL-complete.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] It suffices to show that *st-non-connectivity* is in NL.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This proves co-NL ⊆ NL, and by complementation, NL ⊆ co-NL.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We fix a digraph *G*, a source vertex *s*, and a target vertex *t*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We denote by *R**k* the set of vertices which are reachable from *s* in at most *k* steps.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Note that if *t* is reachable from *s*, it is reachable in at most *n-1* steps, where *n* is the number of vertices, therefore we are reduced to testing whether *t* ∉ *R**n-1*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We remark that *R*0 = { *s* }, and *R**k*+1 is the set of vertices *v* which are either in *R**k*, or the target of an edge *w* → *v* where *w* is in *R**k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This immediately gives an algorithm to decide *t* ∈ *R**n*, by successively computing *R**1*, …, *R**n*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] However, this algorithm uses too much space to solve the problem in NL, since storing a set *R**k* requires one bit per vertex.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The crucial idea of the proof is that instead of computing *R**k*+1 from *R**k*, it is possible to compute the *size* of *R**k*+1 from the *size* of *R**k*, with the help of non-determinism.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] We iterate over vertices and increment a counter for each vertex that is found to belong to *R**k*+1.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] The problem is how to determine whether *v* ∈ *R**k*+1 for a given vertex *v*, when we only have the size of *R**k* available.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] To this end, we iterate over vertices *w*, and for each *w*, we non-deterministically *guess* whether *w* ∈ *R**k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If we guess *w* ∈ *R**k*, and *v* = *w* or there is an edge *w* → *v*, then we determine that *v* belongs to *R**k*+1.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If this fails for all vertices *w*, then *v* does not belong to *R**k*+1.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Thus, the computation that determines whether *v* belongs to *R**k*+1 splits into branches for the different guesses of which vertices belong to *R**k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] A mechanism is needed to make all of these branches abort (reject immediately), except the one where all the guesses were correct.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] For this, when we have made a “yes-guess” that *w* ∈ *R**k*, we *check* this guess, by non-deterministically looking for a path from *s* to *w* of length at most *k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If this check fails, we abort the current branch.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] If it succeeds, we increment a counter of “yes-guesses”.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] On the other hand, we do not check the “no-guesses” that *w* ∉ *R**k* (this would require solving *st-non-connectivity*, which is precisely the problem that we are solving in the first place).
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] However, at the end of the loop over *w*, we check that the counter of “yes-guesses” matches the size of *R**k*, which we know.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Otherwise, all the “yes-guesses” were correct, and there was exactly the right number of them, thus all “no-guesses” were correct as well.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] This concludes the computation of the size of *R**k*+1 from the size of *R**k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/immerman-szelepcsényi-theorem] Finally, we check whether *t* ∈ *R**n-1*, which is possible from the size of *R**n*-2 by the sub-algorithm that is used inside the computation of the size of *R**k*+1.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] In computational complexity theory, non-deterministic space or **NSPACE** is the computational resource describing the memory space for a non-deterministic Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] It is the non-deterministic counterpart of DSPACE.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] The measure NSPACE is used to define the complexity class whose solutions can be determined by a non-deterministic Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] The complexity class NSPACE(*f*(*n*)) is the set of decision problems that can be solved by a non-deterministic Turing machine, *M*, using space *O*(*f*(*n*)), where *n* is the length of the input.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] Several important complexity classes can be defined in terms of *NSPACE*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] The Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem states that NSPACE(*s*(*n*)) is closed under complement for every function *s*(*n*) ≥ log *n*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] A further generalization is ASPACE, defined with alternating Turing machines.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] NSPACE is the non-deterministic counterpart of DSPACE, the class of memory space on a deterministic Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] The measure of space complexity in terms of DSPACE is useful because it represents the total amount of memory that an actual computer would need to solve a given computational problem with a given algorithm.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] The reason is that DSPACE describes the space complexity used by deterministic Turing machines, which can represent actual computers.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] On the other hand, NSPACE describes the space complexity of non-deterministic Turing machines, which are not useful when trying to represent actual computers.
[src:space-complexity-classes/nspace] For this reason, NSPACE is limited in its usefulness to real-world applications.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] In computational complexity theory, **Savitch's theorem**, proved by Walter Savitch in 1970, gives a relationship between deterministic and non-deterministic space complexity.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] In other words, if a nondeterministic Turing machine can solve a problem using $f(n)$ space, a deterministic Turing machine can solve the same problem in the square of that space bound.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Although it seems that nondeterminism may produce exponential gains in time (as formalized in the unproven exponential time hypothesis), Savitch's theorem shows that it has a markedly more limited effect on space requirements.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] That is, for any oracle, replacing every "Turing machine" with "oracle Turing machine" would still result in a theorem.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The proof relies on an algorithm for STCON, the problem of determining whether there is a path between two vertices in a directed graph, which runs in $O\left((\log n)^{2}\right)$ space for n vertices.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The basic idea of the algorithm is to solve recursively a somewhat more general problem, testing the existence of a path from a vertex s to another vertex t that uses at most k edges, for a parameter k given as input.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] STCON is a special case of this problem where k is set large enough to impose no restriction on the paths (for instance, equal to the total number of vertices in the graph, or any larger value).
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] To test for a k -edge path from s to t , a deterministic algorithm can iterate through all vertices u , and recursively search for paths of half the length from s to u and from u to t .
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Because each recursive call halves the parameter k , the number of levels of recursion is $\lceil \log _{2}n\rceil$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Each level requires $O(\log n)$ bits of storage for its function arguments and local variables: k and the vertices s , t , and u require $\lceil \log _{2}n\rceil$ bits each.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The total auxiliary space complexity is thus $O\left((\log n)^{2}\right)$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The input graph is considered to be represented in a separate read-only memory and does not contribute to this auxiliary space bound.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Alternatively, it may be represented as an implicit graph.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Although described above in the form of a program in a high-level language, the same algorithm may be implemented with the same asymptotic space bound on a Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] This algorithm can be applied to an implicit graph whose vertices represent the configurations of a nondeterministic Turing machine and its tape, running within a given space bound $f(n)$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The edges of this graph represent the nondeterministic transitions of the machine, s is set to the initial configuration of the machine, and t is set to a special vertex representing all accepting halting states.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] In this case, the algorithm returns true when the machine has a nondeterministic accepting path, and false otherwise.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] The number of configurations in this graph is $O(2^{f(n)})$ , from which it follows that applying the algorithm to this implicit graph uses space $O(f(n)^{2})$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] Thus by deciding connectivity in a graph representing nondeterministic Turing machine configurations, one can decide membership in the language recognized by that machine, in space proportional to the square of the space used by the Turing machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] That is, the languages that can be recognized by deterministic polynomial-space Turing machines and nondeterministic polynomial-space Turing machines are the same.
[src:space-complexity-classes/savitch-s-theorem] This follows directly from the fact that the square of a polynomial function is still a polynomial function.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The **space complexity** of an algorithm or a data structure is the amount of memory space required to solve an instance of the computational problem as a function of characteristics of the input.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] It is the memory required by an algorithm until it executes completely.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] This includes the memory space used by its inputs, called **input space**, and any other (auxiliary) memory it uses during execution, which is called **auxiliary space**.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] Similar to time complexity, space complexity is often expressed asymptotically in big *O* notation, such as $O(n),$ $O(n\log n),$ $O(n^{\alpha }),$ $O(2^{n}),$ etc., where n is a characteristic of the input influencing space complexity.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] Analogously to time complexity classes DTIME(f(n)) and NTIME(f(n)), the complexity classes DSPACE(f(n)) and NSPACE(f(n)) are the sets of languages that are decidable by deterministic (respectively, non-deterministic) Turing machines that use $O(f(n))$ space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The complexity classes PSPACE and NPSPACE allow f to be any polynomial, analogously to P and NP.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The space hierarchy theorem states that, for all space-constructible functions $f(n),$ there exists a problem that can be solved by a machine with $f(n)$ memory space, but cannot be solved by a machine with asymptotically less than $f(n)$ space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] As a direct corollary, ${\mathsf {PSPACE}}={\mathsf {NPSPACE}}.$ This result is surprising because it suggests that non-determinism can reduce the space necessary to solve a problem only by a small amount.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] In contrast, the exponential time hypothesis conjectures that for time complexity, there can be an exponential gap between deterministic and non-deterministic complexity.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem states that, again for $f\in \Omega (\log(n)),$ ${\mathsf {NSPACE}}(f(n))$ is closed under complementation.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] This shows another qualitative difference between time and space complexity classes, as nondeterministic time complexity classes are not believed to be closed under complementation; for instance, it is conjectured that NP ≠ co-NP.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] L or LOGSPACE is the set of problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine using only $O(\log n)$ memory space with regards to input size.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] Even a single counter that can index the entire n -bit input requires $\log n$ space, so LOGSPACE algorithms can maintain only a constant number of counters or other variables of similar bit complexity.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] LOGSPACE and other sub-linear space complexity is useful when processing large data that cannot fit into a computer's RAM.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] They are related to Streaming algorithms, but only restrict how much memory can be used, while streaming algorithms have further constraints on how the input is fed into the algorithm.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] This class also sees use in the field of pseudorandomness and derandomization, where researchers consider the open problem of whether L = RL.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The corresponding nondeterministic space complexity class is NL.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The term **auxiliary space** refers to space other than that consumed by the input.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] Auxiliary space complexity could be formally defined in terms of a Turing machine with a separate *input tape* which cannot be written to, only read, and a conventional working tape which can be written to.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-complexity] The auxiliary space complexity is then defined (and analyzed) via the working tape.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] In computational complexity theory, the **space hierarchy theorems** are separation results that show that both deterministic and nondeterministic machines can solve more problems in (asymptotically) more space, subject to certain conditions.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] For example, a deterministic Turing machine can solve more decision problems in space *n* log *n* than in space *n*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The somewhat weaker analogous theorems for time are the time hierarchy theorems.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The foundation for the hierarchy theorems lies in the intuition that with either more time or more space comes the ability to compute more functions (or decide more languages).
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The hierarchy theorems are used to demonstrate that the time and space complexity classes form a hierarchy where classes with tighter bounds contain fewer languages than those with more relaxed bounds.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Here we define and prove the space hierarchy theorem.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The space hierarchy theorems rely on the concept of space-constructible functions.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] where SPACE stands for either DSPACE or NSPACE, and o refers to the little o notation.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Formally, a function $f:\mathbb {N} \longrightarrow \mathbb {N}$ is space-constructible if $f(n)\geq \log ~n$ and there exists a Turing machine which computes the function $f(n)$ in space $O(f(n))$ when starting with an input $1^{n}$ , where $1^{n}$ represents a string of *n* consecutive 1s.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Most of the common functions that we work with are space-constructible, including polynomials, exponents, and logarithms.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] For every space-constructible function $f:\mathbb {N} \longrightarrow \mathbb {N}$ , there exists a language L that is decidable in space $O(f(n))$ but not in space $o(f(n))$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The goal is to define a language that can be decided in space $O(f(n))$ but not space $o(f(n))$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] For any machine M that decides a language in space $o(f(n))$ , L will differ in at least one spot from the language of M.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Namely, for some large enough k, M will use space $\leq f(|\langle M\rangle ,10^{k}|)$ on $(\langle M\rangle ,10^{k})$ and will therefore differ at its value.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] On the other hand, L is in ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(f(n))$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] If x is not of the form $\langle M\rangle ,10^{k}$ for some TM M, *reject*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Simulate M on input x for at most $2^{f(|x|)}$ steps (using $f(|x|)$ space).
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] If the simulation tries to use more than $f(|x|)$ space or more than $2^{f(|x|)}$ operations, then *reject*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] If M accepted x during this simulation, then *reject*; otherwise, *accept*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Note on step 3: Execution is limited to $2^{f(|x|)}$ steps in order to avoid the case where M does not halt on the input x.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] That is, the case where M consumes space of only $O(f(x))$ as required, but runs for infinite time.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The above proof holds for the case of PSPACE, but some changes need to be made for the case of NPSPACE.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The crucial point is that while on a deterministic TM, acceptance and rejection can be inverted (crucial for step 4), this is not possible on a non-deterministic machine.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] L can not be decided by a TM using $o(f(n))$ cells.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Assuming L can be decided by some TM M using $o(f(n))$ cells, and following from the Immerman–Szelepcsényi theorem, ${\overline {L}}$ can also be determined by a TM (called ${\overline {M}}$ ) using $o(f(n))$ cells.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] If $w=(\langle {\overline {M}}\rangle ,10^{k})$ (for some large enough k) is in ${\overline {L}}$ then M will reject it, therefore ${\overline {M}}$ accepts w, therefore w is not in ${\overline {L}}$ (contradiction).
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] It seems to be easier to separate classes in space than in time.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Indeed, whereas the time hierarchy theorem has seen little remarkable improvement since its inception, the nondeterministic space hierarchy theorem has seen at least one important improvement by Viliam Geffert in his 2003 paper "Space hierarchy theorem revised".
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] If space is measured as the number of cells used regardless of alphabet size, then ⁠ ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(f(n))={\mathsf {SPACE}}(O(f(n)))$ ⁠ because one can achieve any linear compression by switching to a larger alphabet.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] However, by measuring space in bits, a much sharper separation is achievable for deterministic space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Instead of being defined up to a multiplicative constant, space is now defined up to an additive constant.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] However, because any constant amount of external space can be saved by storing the contents into the internal state, we still have ⁠ ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(f(n))={\mathsf {SPACE}}(f(n)+O(1))$ ⁠.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The proof is similar to the proof of the space hierarchy theorem, but with two complications: The universal Turing machine has to be space-efficient, and the reversal has to be space-efficient.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] One can generally construct universal Turing machines with ⁠ $O(\log(space))$ ⁠ space overhead, and under appropriate assumptions, just ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠ space overhead (which may depend on the machine being simulated).
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] For the reversal, the key issue is how to detect if the simulated machine rejects by entering an infinite (space-constrained) loop.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Simply counting the number of steps taken would increase space consumption by about ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Modify the machine to erase everything and go to a specific configuration A on success.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Use depth-first search to determine whether A is reachable in the space bound from the starting configuration.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The search starts at A and goes over configurations that lead to A.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Because of determinism, this can be done in place and without going into a loop.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] It can also be determined whether the machine exceeds a space bound (as opposed to looping within the space bound) by iterating over all configurations about to exceed the space bound and checking (again using depth-first search) whether the initial configuration leads to any of them.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] This corollary lets us separate various space complexity classes.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] For any natural number k, the function $n^{k}$ is space-constructible.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Savitch's theorem shows that ${\mathsf {NL}}\subseteq {\mathsf {SPACE}}(\log ^{2}n)$ , while the space hierarchy theorem shows that ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(\log ^{2}n)\subsetneq {\mathsf {SPACE}}(n)$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] The result is this corollary along with the fact that TQBF ∉ NL since TQBF is PSPACE-complete.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] This could also be proven using the non-deterministic space hierarchy theorem to show that NL ⊊ NPSPACE, and using Savitch's theorem to show that PSPACE = NPSPACE.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] This last corollary shows the existence of decidable problems that are intractable.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] In other words, their decision procedures must use more than polynomial space.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] There are problems in PSPACE requiring an arbitrarily large exponent to solve; therefore PSPACE does not collapse to DSPACE(*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] To see it, assume the contrary, thus any problem decided in space $O(n)$ is decided in time $O(n^{c})$ , and any problem L decided in space $O(n^{b})$ is decided in time $O((n^{b})^{c})=O(n^{bc})$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] Now ${\mathsf {P}}:=\bigcup _{k\in \mathbb {N} }{\mathsf {DTIME}}(n^{k})$ , thus P is closed under such a change of bound, that is $\bigcup _{k\in \mathbb {N} }{\mathsf {DTIME}}(n^{bk})\subseteq {\mathsf {P}}$ , so $L\in {\mathsf {P}}$ .
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] This implies that for all $b,{\mathsf {SPACE}}(n^{b})\subseteq {\mathsf {P}}\subseteq {\mathsf {SPACE}}(n)$ , but the space hierarchy theorem implies that ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(n^{2})\not \subseteq {\mathsf {SPACE}}(n)$ , and Corollary 6 follows.
[src:space-complexity-classes/space-hierarchy-theorem] It is currently unknown which fail(s) but conjectured that both do, that is that ${\mathsf {SPACE}}(n)$ and ${\mathsf {P}}$ are incomparable -at least for deterministic space.
